<body>

<h1>@HI{{tte}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <em>quote</em> @EM{{@HI{{tte}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{tte}}}} is an informal version of the quotation marker @HI{{to}}.
When @EM{{@HI{{tte}}}} is followed by @KJ{{say}}@HI{{u}},
then the meaning is "the person who is the topic says ...".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{me}}mo@KJ{{going}}kou@EM{{tte}}@KJ{{think}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wondered if I should go there too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="quotation">If</a> there is no following verb then the meaning is ambiguous as the clause could mean "they say ...".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{je-nn}}ha@KJ{{jump}}ranai@EM{{tte}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Jane said she wouldn't dance./They say Jane won't dance.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

